## Passive Effect System

### How It Works

The passive effect system runs in `CompanionBehavior.serverTick`, called from each companion's AI-step hook. Individual companions implement no tick logic.

**While the companion is FOLLOWING (and the owner is within 24 blocks):**
- Every 5 seconds (100 ticks) it (re)applies `passiveEffect()` at `passiveAmplifier()` with a **16-second (320-tick)** duration, `ambient = true`, `visible = false`
- Refreshing a 320-tick effect every 100 ticks keeps the remaining time oscillating between 220 and 320 ticks — always above Night Vision's ~200-tick end-of-effect *flicker window*, so an active effect never strobes. (The original 7s/140-tick plan would have flickered permanently.)
- `visible = false` keeps the HUD clean — only the inventory effect icon shows

**When the companion stops being active (SIT, owner out of range, or unloaded):**
- It simply **stops refreshing**. The effect then fades on its own (≤16s). There is **no active removal call.**
- Rationale: a player may keep many companions. Per-companion teardown either (a) makes a sitting companion cancel an effect a *following* companion is still sustaining, or (b) requires a per-tick scan to check for other providers. Letting the effect lapse naturally avoids both — it scales flat to hundreds of companions and is self-correcting (the last active provider's refresh is simply the last one that lands).

**Important constraints:**
- Effect amplifier is always 0 (Level I) — never higher, by design
- Effects are intentionally "background" — the weakest tier of the effect family
- Multiple companions granting the same effect don't stack — they all refresh the same single effect instance
- **Trade-off:** sitting your *last* companion leaves the effect lingering up to its duration (~16s, with vanilla's normal wear-off flicker in the final 10s). Accepted as a fair cost for the performance and correctness wins above.

